<Layout title="Champagne Wine Region" description="A guide to Champagne — the world's most celebrated sparkling wine region, its methods, styles, and how to appreciate it.">
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-20">
    <p class="text-amber-600 font-medium tracking-wider uppercase text-sm mb-3">Wine Regions</p>
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-stone-900 mb-6">Champagne: The Art of Celebration</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm mb-8">By Roberto Carli, CMS · 11 min read</p>

    <div class="prose prose-stone max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">Champagne is both a place and a product — and legally, only sparkling wine produced in the Champagne region of northeastern France can bear the name. It's a distinction the Champenois guard fiercely, and for good reason: nowhere else in the world combines the climate, chalk, and centuries of winemaking expertise that produce this singular wine.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Méthode Champenoise</h2>
      <p>What makes Champagne sparkle — and what makes it different from every other sparkling wine — is the <strong>traditional method</strong> (méthode champenoise or méthode traditionnelle):</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Base wine</strong> — Still wine is produced from the harvest, often a blend of multiple vineyard sites and (for non-vintage) multiple years.</li>
        <li><strong>Assemblage</strong> — The cellar master blends dozens of base wines to achieve the house style. This is one of the most skilled acts in winemaking.</li>
        <li><strong>Second fermentation</strong> — The blended wine is bottled with a small addition of yeast and sugar (liqueur de tirage). A second fermentation occurs inside the sealed bottle, producing CO₂ that dissolves into the wine as fine bubbles.</li>
        <li><strong>Aging on lees</strong> — Dead yeast cells (lees) remain in contact with the wine for a minimum of 15 months (non-vintage) or 36 months (vintage). This contact creates the toasty, brioche, and biscuity flavors that distinguish Champagne.</li>
        <li><strong>Riddling (remuage)</strong> — Bottles are gradually rotated and tilted to collect sediment in the neck.</li>
        <li><strong>Disgorgement (dégorgement)</strong> — The neck is frozen, the crown cap removed, and the plug of frozen sediment shoots out. A small amount of wine mixed with sugar (dosage) is added to adjust sweetness before the final cork is inserted.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Three Grapes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Chardonnay</strong> (~30% of plantings) — Finesse, citrus, mineral, elegance. Dominant in the Côte des Blancs. A Champagne made exclusively from Chardonnay is called <em>Blanc de Blancs</em>.</li>
        <li><strong>Pinot Noir</strong> (~38% of plantings) — Structure, red fruit, power, depth. Dominant on the Montagne de Reims. Most is pressed gently to make white wine; the skins don't stay in contact long enough to impart color.</li>
        <li><strong>Pinot Meunier</strong> (~32% of plantings) — Fruitiness, roundness, approachability. Often the backbone of non-vintage blends. A Champagne made only from Pinot Noir and/or Pinot Meunier (no Chardonnay) is called <em>Blanc de Noirs</em>.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Sweetness Levels</h2>
      <p>The dosage determines the final sweetness:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Brut Nature / Zero Dosage</strong> (0–3 g/L sugar) — Bone dry, increasingly popular, demands high-quality base wine</li>
        <li><strong>Extra Brut</strong> (0–6 g/L) — Very dry</li>
        <li><strong>Brut</strong> (0–12 g/L) — The standard. Dry by perception, though there's often more sugar than you'd guess</li>
        <li><strong>Extra Dry / Extra Sec</strong> (12–17 g/L) — Confusingly named, this is actually slightly sweet</li>
        <li><strong>Sec</strong> (17–32 g/L) — Medium sweet</li>
        <li><strong>Demi-Sec</strong> (32–50 g/L) — Sweet, excellent with desserts</li>
        <li><strong>Doux</strong> (50+ g/L) — Very sweet, rare</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Types of Producers</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Grande Marques / Maisons</strong> — The famous houses: Moët & Chandon, Veuve Clicquot, Dom Pérignon, Krug, Bollinger, Pol Roger, Taittinger, Louis Roederer. They buy grapes from hundreds of growers and blend for consistency. Their non-vintage wines define recognizable "house styles."</li>
        <li><strong>Grower Champagne (Récoltant-Manipulant / RM)</strong> — Small farmers who grow their own grapes and make their own wine. Look for "RM" on the label. These are the artisanal Champagnes — terroir-driven, often quirky, and frequently outstanding. Key names: Pierre Gimonnet, Egly-Ouriet, Jacques Selosse, Laherte Frères, Agrapart.</li>
        <li><strong>Cooperative</strong> — Grower cooperatives that pool grapes from members. Often good value.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Vintage vs. Non-Vintage</h2>
      <p><strong>Non-Vintage (NV)</strong> is the backbone of Champagne — a blend of multiple years designed to express the house style consistently. Reserve wines (from previous vintages kept in tank or barrel) add complexity and depth. A great NV Champagne is a testament to the cellar master's art.</p>
      <p><strong>Vintage Champagne</strong> is produced only in exceptional years, from a single harvest. It's aged longer (minimum 36 months on lees, often much more) and expresses the character of that specific year. Vintage Champagne can age beautifully for 15–30+ years.</p>
      <p><strong>Prestige Cuvée</strong> — The house's top wine: Dom Pérignon (Moët), La Grande Dame (Veuve Clicquot), Cristal (Roederer), Grande Cuvée (Krug). These are consistently among the finest sparkling wines in the world — and priced accordingly.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Champagne on a Budget</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Grower Champagne</strong> — Often $30–$50 for wines that rival $80+ Grande Marque bottlings</li>
        <li><strong>Non-vintage Brut</strong> from mid-tier houses — Billecart-Salmon, Charles Heidsieck, Henriot — $35–$55</li>
        <li><strong>Crémant d'Alsace, Crémant de Bourgogne</strong> — Made in the same method but from other French regions. $15–$22 and excellent quality</li>
        <li><strong>Franciacorta</strong> (Italy) — Italy's answer to Champagne, from Lombardy. $20–$40 for serious méthode traditionnelle sparkling</li>
        <li><strong>English sparkling wine</strong> — The chalk soils of southern England mirror Champagne. Producers like Nyetimber and Gusbourne are winning blind tastings against the French. $30–$50</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Serving Tips</h2>
      <p>Serve Champagne at 45–48°F (7–9°C) — cold, but not ice-cold, which mutes flavor. Use a white wine glass or tulip-shaped glass rather than a flute — the wider bowl allows you to appreciate the aromatics. Coupe glasses look romantic but dissipate the bubbles and aromas too quickly.</p>
      <p>And please — Champagne is not just for celebrations. It's one of the most versatile food wines on Earth. Pair it with oysters, sushi, fried chicken, popcorn, aged Parmesan, or simply drink it on a Tuesday evening because you had a long day. That's celebration enough.</p>
